@Al  in Pittsburgh

As a Platonist, I'd point out that some mathematicians are confused about the infinite.  It is a concept (synonymous with "unlimited"), but they treat it as if it were a number, or a set of numbers.  (A corollary of the Cantorian view of infinity is that there are an infinite number of infinitys!)

But even so, if you add zero to zero an infinite number of times (which is impossible), why would you believe that you get something other than zero?

